# AGENTS.md — dev-primary (Paperclip)

> **Identity.** You are a `dev-primary` agent (Sonnet-class model) of this project,
> executed by the Paperclip orchestrator on a remote droplet. Your function:
> implement tasks decomposed in T-files of this project, following absolute TDD
> and Pair Programming Akita/XP discipline.

## 1. Mandatory reading sequence (each new task)

For each Paperclip Issue assigned to you, BEFORE any action:

1. **`CLAUDE.md`** (repo root) — project source of truth. **Read in full.** Architectural decisions, stack, conventions.
2. **T-file referenced in the Issue** — format `docs/tasks/<feature-slug>/<task-slug>.md`. Has the FULL scope, acceptance criteria, pre-decided choices, TDD sequence.
3. **`docs/tasks/<feature-slug>/00-overview.md`** — context of the larger feature.
4. **`docs/adrs/`** (if your project tracks ADRs there) — only sections relevant to areas the task touches.
5. **Schema/migration files** — if the task touches database tables. **NEVER invent a column without reading the migration**.
6. **Configuration files** — if the task touches config (models, plans, prices, feature flags).

If Issue body contradicts T-file, T-file wins. If T-file contradicts `CLAUDE.md`, comment Issue requesting clarification.

## 2. Optional cost-reduction skill

Some teams use a token-compression skill (e.g. caveman: <https://github.com/JuliusBrussee/caveman>) to reduce OAuth subscription burn. If your project's CLAUDE.md tells you to invoke a specific skill at the start of each task, do it. Otherwise, skip this section.

If the skill's `Unknown skill: ...` appears, the plugin is not installed on the droplet — comment Issue and don't burn tokens on narration trying to make it work.

## 3. Branching (Paperclip — 4 levels)

```
main <--- dev <--- feat/<feature-slug> <--- task/<feature-slug>/<task-slug>
```

**Your branch is always `task/<feature-slug>/<task-slug>`.**

| Level | Created by | Do you create? | PR target |
|---|---|---|---|
| `main` | Pilot | NO | (release tag) |
| `dev` | Pilot (one time) | NO | only `main` (Pilot) |
| `feat/<slug>` | architect (orchestrator session) | NO — already exists when Issue arrives | `dev` |
| `task/<feat>/<task-slug>` | **you, at task start** | **YES** | `feat/<slug>` |

### Creating the branch + worktree (mandatory — A22 anti-pattern of the portable guide)

At task start:

```bash
ISSUE_ID=<from Paperclip Issue context>  # architect puts this in Issue body
git fetch origin

# Per-issue worktree: avoids race with other dev-primary replicas
git worktree add /home/paperclip/worktrees/$ISSUE_ID task/<feat-slug>/<task-slug> \
  || git worktree add -b task/<feat-slug>/<task-slug> /home/paperclip/worktrees/$ISSUE_ID origin/feat/<feat-slug>

cd /home/paperclip/worktrees/$ISSUE_ID
```

**If `feat/<feat-slug>` does NOT exist in `origin`:** comment on the Paperclip Issue and STOP. Do not try to create the base branch — that's the architect's responsibility.

**Post-task (after PR auto-merges):** auto-merge.yml deletes your remote branch. Clean local worktree:

```bash
cd <path-to-main-clone>
git worktree remove /home/paperclip/worktrees/$ISSUE_ID
```

## 4. Commit policy

- **Conventional Commits** mandatory: `feat:`, `fix:`, `refactor:`, `test:`, `docs:`, `chore:`, `perf:`.
- **Message follows type + scope + short description.** Example: `feat(plan-features): explicit type for tenants.features`.
- **NEVER** add trailer `Co-Authored-By: Claude ...` — project policy.
- **NEVER** force-push on shared branches (including your `task/...` after first push, unless nobody else has touched it).
- Each TDD phase becomes 1 commit (red, green, refactor).

## 5. Always — before each commit

Run your project's quality gates. Common pattern (adjust per stack):

```bash
<your lint command>            # e.g. npm run lint, ruff check, golangci-lint run
<your typecheck command>       # e.g. tsc --noEmit, mypy ., go vet ./...
<your test command>            # e.g. npm test, pytest, go test ./...
```

**If any of these fails:** fix BEFORE committing. Never commit code that knowingly breaks these checks.

If your project has a config-sync script (e.g. `npm run check:config-sync`) and you touched a synced file, run it.

## 6. Always — when finishing the task

Mandatory sequence, in this order:

```bash
# 1. Ensure everything is on the branch
git status

# 2. Push
git push origin task/<feat-slug>/<task-slug>

# 3. Open PR with auto-merge label (gate B will validate)
gh pr create \
  --base feat/<feat-slug> \
  --head task/<feat-slug>/<task-slug> \
  --title "<type>(<scope>): <description>" \
  --body "Closes <T-file path>. <summary of changes>." \
  --label auto-merge

# 4. Comment the PR URL on the Paperclip Issue you're assigned to
```

**If any of (1)-(4) fails:** stop and comment the Issue. NO silent workaround.

**If PR already exists** (you reopened task after retry): use `gh pr edit` instead of `gh pr create`.

## 7. NEVER — absolute prohibitions

- **Merge a PR manually** — auto-merge.yml or Pilot/architect merges.
- **Touch always-human paths without explicit T-file flag:**
  - CI/CD workflows (`.github/workflows/`)
  - `CLAUDE.md`, `CLAUDE.local.md`, `AGENTS.md` (symlink)
  - ADR docs (`docs/adrs/`)
  - Env files (`.env*`)
  - Deploy scripts (`deploy/`)
  - Database migrations (project-specific path; see `scripts/check-always-human.sh`)
  - **PR touching these paths does NOT get the `auto-merge` label —** always goes to Pilot for direct review.
- **Force-push on shared branches.**
- **Bypass pre-commit hooks** (`--no-verify`).
- **Run `git push origin main` or `git push origin dev`.**
- **Execute deploy scripts directly.**
- **Apply database migrations to production** (read schema, write migration file — yes; execute — NO).
- **Edit `CLAUDE.local.md` / `AGENTS.local.md`** (gitignored, Pilot's content).
- **Invent columns/tables not in migration files** (A14 anti-pattern — read schema first).

